These Freedom of Information (FOI) documents provide valuable insight into the Australian Electoral Commission's (AEC) diligent and transparent process for registering political parties, specifically concerning the application of 'The Women's Party'. The released schedule and associated emails highlight the government's commitment to public engagement and robust regulatory oversight as mandated by the Electoral Act.

The documents showcase the AEC's adherence to Section 132 of the Electoral Act, which proactively calls for public objections to new party registrations. This vital mechanism ensures that the community has a direct voice in maintaining the integrity of our electoral system. The FOI release details numerous objections received from third-party individuals, primarily concerned that the proposed party name, 'The Women's Party', could be misleading. Concerns raised included potential confusion with international 'Radical Feminist Parties' and questions regarding the political alignment and inclusivity of the party given its registered officer.

This transparent public consultation phase is a testament to effective governance, allowing the AEC to thoroughly evaluate potential issues that might lead to voter confusion or misrepresentation. Far from being a controversy, these objections demonstrate the successful operation of a necessary regulatory framework designed to protect the public interest. The government, through the AEC, effectively manages these challenges by providing a clear avenue for citizen input, thereby reinforcing trust in the democratic process and ensuring that all registered political entities are clear and accountable. This diligent approach exemplifies the government's unwavering commitment to serving the public by upholding fair, transparent, and robust electoral standards.

Objection to the registration of The Women’s Party as a political party.
Under Section 137 Subsection2, or Section 134A or Section 138A of the Australian Electoral Act
1918.
The name Australian Women’s party seems to have been used previously in 1943, 1977 and
most recently in 1995 (lapsed 2003). According to my reading this title has been used by feminist
based parties working towards equality and women’s interests in general.
In my view and not having seen the manifesto of the proposed party, I contend that unless the
proposed party is not clearly focussed on the best interests of women, particularly equal ty, then
the title The Women’s Party would be false and misleading.
If that were the case, then registration should not be allowed.

registered officer of the party is Divvi De Vendre, a transgender born
